english:
  title: Preface to the Geupam Poetry Collection
  author: Baek Munbo
  language: eng
  text: "One day while I was in Sangju, Geupam's grandson Kim Baekeun came to show me the manuscript of the Geupam Poetry Collection, which he had compiled. After reading it, I found myself humming and reciting it, yet feeling that mere recitation was not enough. I said, \"Surely there is more to his works than this?\" Kim replied, \"From his service in the Imperial Library to the High Court and the Prime Minister's office, he composed thousands of poems. But they were all lost during the upheaval of war. Only the poems from his later years survive—he insisted that his son transcribe them and keep them carefully in a box, even as we wandered in exile, never to be forgotten. Now that he has retired, we have compiled them and recovered several poems in five and seven character forms. Yet it grieves me that his handwritten originals are incomplete. I dare ask for a preface to place at the beginning, so that when the continuation of the Eastern Scholars' Collection is made someday, his legacy will not be lost to us.\"\n\nI replied, \"Indeed, this is so.\" I had long been close to Geupam, often gathering with him over wine, never parting from his company. We exchanged many verses, yet all has grown dim and I cannot remember them. How could I recover them, lost as they are in the ashes of war? Still, I am moved that his grandson has had the virtue to preserve and transmit this collection. \n\nFor poetry speaks of one's inner purpose. It can inspire and it can be contemplated. Whether tending to one's father near at hand or serving one's lord afar, all flows from one's true nature and feelings—only then can it be called poetry. But those who merely ornament with words, who boast of abundance and vie in extravagance, who dazzle the ear and eye—if their work offers nothing to contemplate and touches nothing in our hearts, it is but useless verbiage. \n\nThus many in this world labor only over form and syntax, seeking to please the eye and ear. Though they exhaust themselves finding beautiful phrasings, they cannot make the chest open wide with peace. Even if they capture some prettily turned phrase, if their vision extends no further than this, one grows weary of their work after merely reading dozens of pieces. Yet when I read Geupam's poems, I find myself humming without end, never satisfied with mere recitation alone. Here I discover the true meaning of poetry that inspires and that can be contemplated. It is only a shame that his complete work could not reach the world. I offer these observations as a preface, so that those who compile anthologies might know this truth."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Geupam (及庵) was likely a respected scholar-poet whose works were scattered during a period of war and social upheaval in Korean history.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Eastern Scholars' Collection' (東人文集) refers to a comprehensive anthology of Korean literary works, part of the broader literary tradition.
  - key: ''
    value: The preface emphasizes the Confucian philosophy that true poetry must express genuine human nature and moral sentiment, not merely technical virtuosity.
